### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

forms

### Description

I saw #65769 but I think this case is different:

As library developer, I was trying to migrate our custom controls to the new `FormValueControl`.
So a very common scenario will be, that our custom controls implementing `FormValueControl` will be used with `ngModel` / `formControl`. 
While this very basic scenario works very well, we usually also have `Validator` implemented on those custom controls.
Which no longer works.

To be very precise, we basically have this setup:

```ts
/** Library code */
@Component({selector:  `library-form-control`})
class MyCustomControl implements FormValueControl<number>, Validator {
  ...
}

/** Client / library consumer code */
@Component({template: `<library-form-control [(ngModel)]="value"})
class ClientForm {
  value = 0;
}
```

### Proposed solution

I fully understand, that validation should be declared on the form schema. But ONLY in cases where `ngModel` / `formControl` are used it would be very helpful for migration, if `NG_VALIDATORS` would still be picked up by `ngModel` / `formControl` even if `FormControlValue` is used. 

### Alternatives considered

`transformedValue` is really nice, but does not help in all cases. We also have non parsing related validation.

We could just announce this as a breaking change, but it is expected that this has a stronger impact.  Especially since this is hard to detect since there are not type errors.

Just staying on `ControlValueAccessor` for ever, which obviously works.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

zone.js

### Is this a regression?

No вҖ” the bug is present in the initial vitest support (`zone.js/plugins/vitest-patch`) and is still present in 0.16.2.

### Description

`zone.js/plugins/vitest-patch` re-wraps `describe`/`suite`/`it`/`test` for zone support and also replaces all of their modifiers (`skip`, `only`, `todo`, `each`, `for`, `skipIf`, `runIf`, `concurrent`, `sequential`, `shuffle`). The replacement treats **every** modifier as an `.each`-style curried factory **and** calls the plain base function instead of the modifier, which breaks all of them:

```js
// packages/zone.js/lib/vitest/vitest.ts (fesm2015/vitest-patch.js in the dist)

// describe modifiers:
for (const factoryName of DESCRIBE_FACTORY_NAMES) {
  context[methodName][factoryName] = function (...factoryArgs) {
    const originalDescribeFn = originalVitestFn.apply(this, factoryArgs); // (1)
    return function (...args) {                                          // (2)
      args[1] = wrapDescribeInZone(args[1]);
      return originalDescribeFn.apply(this, args);
    };
  };
}

// it/test modifiers:
for (const factoryName of TEST_FACTORY_NAMES) {
  context[methodName][factoryName] = function (...factoryArgs) {
    return function (...args) {                                          // (3)
      args[1] = wrapTestInZone(args[1]);
      return originalVitestFn.apply(this, factoryArgs).apply(this, args);
    };
  };
}
```

Concrete consequences:

- **`describe.skip('name', fn)` registers a NORMAL suite вҖ” the skip is silently dropped and the tests run** (and can fail). At (1), `originalVitestFn.apply(this, ['name', fn])` is just `describe('name', fn)`, executed immediately; the function returned at (2) is never called by user code, and the suite body registered at (1) is also not zone-wrapped.
- **`it.skip(...)`, `it.todo(...)`, `it.only(...)`, etc. silently vanish from the run.** The modifier returns the inner function at (3), which user code never invokes, so nothing is registered at all. Skip/todo counts read 0 and the tests disappear from the report without a trace.
- **Even the genuinely curried modifiers (`each`, `for`) are broken**, because (1)/(3) call `originalVitestFn` (plain `describe`/`it`) instead of `originalVitestFn[factoryName]`. `describe.each(table)('name %s', fn)` executes `describe(table)` вҖ” the table object as the suite name.
- Chained modifiers (`it.skip.each(...)`) and props like `describe.todo` are likewise broken.

The unpatched originals are stashed under `Zone.__symbol__('describe')` / `('suite')` / `('it')` / `('test')`, which is what makes the workaround below possible.

The fix shape: non-curried modifiers (`skip`, `only`, `todo`, `concurrent`, `sequential`, `shuffle`) need the same wrapping as the base function but delegating to `originalVitestFn[factoryName]`; curried ones (`each`, `for`, `skipIf`, `runIf`) need `originalVitestFn[factoryName](...factoryArgs)` first, then arg-wrapping in the returned registrar. (`skipIf`/`runIf` are condition-curried: `it.skipIf(cond)(name, fn)`.)

### Please provide a link to a minimal reproduction of the bug

Inline reproduction вҖ” any zone-based Angular CLI v21 app using the `unit-test` builder with `runner: "vitest"` (which auto-loads `zone.js/plugins/vitest-patch`), or any Vitest setup that imports `zone.js`, `zone.js/testing`'s Proxy/SyncTest zone specs, and `zone.js/plugins/vitest-patch`:

```ts
// repro.spec.ts
describe.skip('skipped suite', () => {
  it('must not run', () => {
    throw new Error('describe.skip ran anyway');
  });
});

describe('modifiers', () => {
  it.skip('skipped test', () => {
    throw new Error('never');
  });
  it.todo('todo test');
  it('control', () => {
    expect(true).toBe(true);
  });
});
```

Expected (plain Vitest): `1 passed | 2 skipped | 1 todo`, no failures.

Actual with `vitest-patch`: the `describe.skip` suite runs and fails with `describe.skip ran anyway`; `it.skip` and `it.todo` are absent from the report entirely вҖ” `1 failed | 1 passed`, skipped/todo counts are 0.

### Please provide the exception or error you saw

No exception from zone.js itself вҖ” that's the dangerous part. Suites the author explicitly skipped (e.g. because they're known-broken) execute and fail, and `it.skip`/`it.todo` tests silently disappear, so a migrated suite under-reports its own size with no signal.

Observed while migrating a 433-file / 735-test Angular 21 suite from Karma to the `@angular/build:unit-test` Vitest runner: every `describe.skip` suite began executing (NG0201 failures etc.), and the run's skip count read 0 while the total test count dropped versus Karma.

### Workaround

Restore the original modifiers from the stashed unpatched functions in a `setupFiles` entry (safe as long as the suite doesn't rely on zone wrapping inside `.only`/`.each` bodies вҖ” skipped/todo bodies never execute anyway):

```ts
const g = globalThis as any;
const zoneSymbol = g.Zone.__symbol__;
const MODIFIERS = [
  'skip', 'skipIf', 'runIf', 'only', 'concurrent',
  'sequential', 'shuffle', 'todo', 'each', 'for'
];
for (const name of ['describe', 'suite', 'it', 'test']) {
  const original = g[zoneSymbol(name)];
  const patched = g[name];
  if (!original || !patched || original === patched) continue;
  for (const mod of MODIFIERS) {
    if (typeof original[mod] === 'function') {
      patched[mod] = original[mod].bind(original);
    }
  }
}
```

### Please provide the environment you discovered this bug in

- zone.js: 0.16.2
- vitest: 4.1.10 (browser mode, `@vitest/browser-playwright` 4.1.10, headless Chromium)
- @angular/build: 21.2.9 (`unit-test` builder, `runner: "vitest"`)
- @angular/core: 21.2.10
- OS: Windows 11, Node 20.19

### Anything else?

The `beforeEach`/`afterEach`/`beforeAll`/`afterAll` patching in the same file is fine вҖ” only the modifier/factory loops are affected.

## Problem

Currently there is no explicit way to know when a `@defer` block has finished loading and has been rendered.

The current alternatives require indirectly detecting this state, for example by:

* querying a deferred child with `viewChild()`;
* using an `effect()` to detect when a `viewChild()` becomes available.;

## Proposed API

Support an optional `loaded` callback (or event) on `@defer`, similar to how `@for` supports the `track` clause.:

```html
@defer (on timer(500ms); loaded: onDeferredLoaded) {
  <app-foo />
} @placeholder {
  Loading...
}
```

or any equivalent API that provides a notification when the deferred block has been instantiated and rendered.

## Motivation

An explicit event would make it easier to write cleaner code without relying on `effect()`.

Eg.:
```ts
import { Component, viewChild, effect } from '@angular/core';
import { bootstrapApplication } from '@angular/platform-browser';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-foo',
  template: `Foo!`,
})
export class Foo {}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-root',
  imports: [Foo],
  template: `
    @defer(on timer(500ms); loaded: onDeferredLoaded) {
      <app-foo />
    } @placeholder {
      <div>Loading</div>
    }
  `,
})
export class App {
  foo = viewChild(Foo);

  constructor() {
    console.log('foo', this.foo()); // this.foo() is undefined
    effect(() => {
      console.log('foo', this.foo()); // this.foo() is undefined and after 500ms is defined
    });
  }

 onDeferredLoaded() {
      console.log('foo', this.foo()); // this.foo() is defined
  }
}

bootstrapApplication(App);
```
